What we basically need to do is replace those javascript hightlighting with ts. AFAIK most of the examples uses typescript so it should be quite safe to replace javascript with typescript here, but it might break some of the examples

@JWO719 This repo already has `typescript` as a dev dependency so there could be another dgeni processor that only checks public entry points and from `export` statements figures out what is an alias (this would work as `tslint` extension as well).

```
import * as fs from 'fs';
import { createSourceFile, SyntaxKind, ScriptTarget, ExportDeclaration, Statement } from 'typescript';

const filename = 'src/internal/operators/index.ts';
const sourceFile = createSourceFile(filename, fs.readFileSync(filename).toString(), ScriptTarget.ES5);

const isExportDeclaration = (s: Statement): s is ExportDeclaration => s.kind === SyntaxKind.ExportDeclaration;

sourceFile.statements.forEach(statement => {
  if (isExportDeclaration(statement) && statement.exportClause) {
    statement.exportClause.elements.forEach(element => {
      if (element.propertyName && element.name) {
        const exportAlias = element.name.text;
        const exportName = element.propertyName.text;

        console.log(exportName, '=>', exportAlias);
      }
    });
  }
});

// ...
// this prints the following output:
// mergeMap => flatMap
```

This is expecting that all aliases are going to be just renamed exports that are already exported (like `flatMap` and `mergeMap`).  I think it's a question whether also exports like these should be considered as alias:

```
